[1] Portugal: poor vaccination coverage
Date: Fri 24 Apr 2020
Source: MNA International [abridged, edited]
https://www.macaubusiness.com/portugal-one-in-10-children-aged-13-months-unprotected-against-measles/


One in 10 children aged 13 months in Portugal had no measles vaccine at the end of last year [2019], the National Immunization Programme (NIP) reported on Fri [24 Apr 2020].

The document, which was seen by Lusa and which assesses compliance with the NIP in 2019, said that at 13 months of age, 14% of children had not yet started vaccination against measles or the invasive meningococcal disease of group C, which must be administered at 12 months.

"This puts children of this age at risk of measles outbreaks if they come into contact with cases, as they are mostly together in day-care centres, without having herd immunity, which is granted from 95% coverage," the DGS document warns.

In a statement to Lusa, the coordinator of the NIP said that although the meningococcal disease does not usually cause outbreaks, "it is a very serious disease in young children," and "the sooner they are immunised the better."

"We have herd immunity for meningococcal disease C, but at 12 months they should get vaccinated as soon as possible so they are not susceptible," she said, adding: "The same happens for measles, but for measles, it is worse because it is much more contagious and can cause outbreaks. We have measles all over Europe and in the 4 corners of the world, and that really cannot be neglected."

