[4] Bolivia: atypical case
Date: Sat 25 Apr 2020
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/bolivia-measles-case-reported-after-19-years-in-santa-cruz-76112/


In Bolivia, director of Epidemiology Virgilio Prieto reported Thursday [23 Apr 2020] that an atypical case of measles was reported in the city of Santa Cruz.

The patient is a 29-year-old pediatrician with no travel history, no contact with tourists, and she was vaccinated as a child.

"We say it is an atypical case because despite being vaccinated, she presented signs and symptoms of the disease: fever, cough, runny nose, and skin spots," the authority explained in a statement.

The patient underwent tests and in all of them came out positive; it is suspected that the contagion may have originated in an unvaccinated minor, taking into account the care provided by the health professional.

"For about 20 years, measles was eradicated, [and now] the virus is spreading again in the region."

Before the outbreak of the disease, the Ministry of Health activated control measures, such as isolation of patients and investigation of contacts. Vaccination is also being carried out in the patients' close environments; likewise, the appearance of suspicious cases is being followed up, and active searches for other cases are being carried out.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Between 1 Jan and 10 Apr 2020, 7 countries reported 1104 confirmed cases in the Region of the Americas: Argentina (54 cases, including one death), Brazil (909 cases, including 4 deaths), Canada (one case), Chile (2 cases), Mexico (124 cases), the United States of America (12 cases), and Uruguay (2 cases); (http://outbreaknewstoday.com/measles-in-the-americas-1100-confirmed-cases-to-date-buenos-aires-mexico-city-and-sao-paulo-41981/).

Published medical research indicates that vaccine failure due to waning immunity can occur, despite multiple doses of measles vaccine. Measles vaccine-acquired immunity is reported to wane in at least 5 percent of cases within 10 to 15 years after vaccination. Moreover, exposure to natural measles may be necessary for the maintenance of protective antibodies in vaccinated persons. The Vaccine Research Group at Minnesota's Mayo Clinic reports that up to 10 percent of persons who receive 2 doses of MMR vaccine "fail to develop protective humoral immunity, and those antibody levels wane over time, which can result in infection." (National Vaccine Information Center https://www.nvic.org/vaccines-and-diseases/Measles/measles-vaccine-effectiveness.aspx. See full report for more complete information on vaccine effectiveness.) - Mod.LK]

